<p>Perhaps Kyoto's most iconic temple, Kinkaku-ji stands like a golden jewel reflected in its surrounding pond. Built in 1397 as a retirement villa for Shogun Ashikaga Yoshimitsu, it was converted into a Zen temple after his death.</p>

<div class="highlight">
The top two floors are completely covered in gold leaf, creating a stunning mirror image in the carefully designed pond below.
</div>

<p>The temple represents different architectural styles on each floor: the first floor follows the Heian period's shinden-zukuri style, the second floor uses the bukke-zukuri style of samurai residences, and the third floor is built in the Chinese zen-style.</p>

<p>Tragically, the original structure was burned down by a disturbed monk in 1950 (inspiring Yukio Mishima's novel "The Temple of the Golden Pavilion"), but was rebuilt exactly as before in 1955.</p>

